value.0: A mountain of a man with a beard as thick and tangled as a troll's mane, Gormun booms with a voice that can silence a bar brawl. Though gruff and intimidating at first glance, his eyes twinkle with a hint of amusement, and he takes a certain fatherly pride in supplying the guild with the tools they need to "redistribute" wealth.

Elara, a slender elf with hair as black as midnight, glides silently behind the bar, her every movement efficient and unseen. Her sharp ears miss nothing, catching whispers and secrets exchanged between guild members. Despite her seemingly aloof demeanor, Elara holds a wealth of knowledge about the Undercity and its denizens. A trusted confidante of the guild leadership, she serves strong drinks and even stronger advice, all with a quiet smile that never quite reaches her eyes.

The minstrel-thief, liar and braggart Gizch amassed many treasures in his medium-length but extremely eventful life. One of them is the suit of leathers you now hold in your hands, fashioned(or so Gizch claimed) from the tanned hides of a monastic order of hobgoblins and still imbued with their mage-barring serenity. The word of Gizch could never be trusted, but these leathers will prove more reliable.

Pours a clear reddish amber with a frothy, foamy head that settles into a thin sudsy lacing. It has aromas of lightly toasted grains, a apple and grape fruitiness with a little orange zest, earthy yeast, and a soft floral hoppiness. 

Pleasant tasting, toasted grassy grains and caramelized sugary maltiness, earthy, peppery yeastiness, a light fruitiness, a bit apple and orange, spicy hops with a soft, but lingering bitterness, a slight taste of alcohol towards the end, the alcohol provides a subtle warming in the palate, and a dry grainy, subtle fruity, spicy finish.

Ice wine is a type of dessert wine produced from grapes that have been frozen while still on the vine. This results in a smaller amount of more concentrated, very sweet wine. Due to the labour-intense and risky production process resulting in relatively small amounts of wine, ice wines are generally quite expensive.

This armor is made for those who make it their profession to hunt others. Be it people, or creatures, these were designed to make to tracking easier. It comes complete with various devices to aid in orienteering, and numerous pockets to hold things in while out on adventures.
Piecemeal or complete armors of this grade are meager protection, no better than garments made of cloth or even rags.

Woven intricately of fine black silks, blackened leathers, and steel, this armor is so light that it is even more comfortable than normal clothing.  It is also crafted so finely, that the wearer's agility seems to be improved. A mage has had his hand in it's making at some point, because it seems to have magical properties.
A simple, confident looking cloth. Wearing this, some may doubt the thought that you may actually kill them...

The Dueling Suit is specially designed for use by the nimble fighting adventurer. The light fabrics allow for excellent manueverability, while the protective magics ensure an adequate defense against attacks.
The Nimble Suit was designed with the purpose of flexibility and camouflage in mind.  It offers little in the way of physical protection, but is most useful to those in certain, shady occupations.
Designed for an especially picky rogue (you know who you are) by Arwen E'lyn.  This outfit has full sleeves to the wrist, a useful belt with pouches, and rakish boots.
This suit was made for those who rely on quick movements to help them dodge and avoid blows. It doesn't offer much protection against blows, however it'll help you avoid them.
Piecemeal or complete armors of this grade are meager protection, no better than garments made of cloth or even rags.

Target the Magical Ammo Bag on the following items to restock them at a nominal charge:

1. Bolt
2. Arrow
3. Bullets
4. Darts
5. Shurikens
6. Throwing axes

Please note after restocking, the items will be flagged as stolen and non-transferrable to prevent you from selling them back at a profit.
A simple iron hook that could be used for climbing.
Sold usually for squeaky chairs or golems, this is a large bucket filled with generic grease; not much else to say for it.

A bundle of hemp rope.

[OOC: You can use this to overcome certain obstacles in the game]
Crafted to look like a mundane dagger, this item's magical properties have been cleverly concealed to make any thief look a bit more mundane.
Crafted of a matte, darkened iron, this blade won't dare reveal itself as it plunges into the back of its desired mark.

This weapon bears the mark of the dwarf Barun, a Master Blacksmith who worked from a makeshift forge in the Uthgardt village of Beorunna's Well. He forged it late in 1373 DR, to aid the war effort against Lady Aribeth the Betrayer, who was then marching against the northern city of Neverwinter and the Lords' Alliance.

They say a great duelist is only as good as his feet. But what is there to say about the greatest duelist? History long remembers the mistake of Sevenchen of Halruua. So skilled with the rapier, so confident was he that he began to bore of besting every man and woman that face him. He began to fight in less and less traditional ways, humiliating his foes with deafeat while blindfolded, deafened, underwater.

Despite it all, only the last duel is the only one the bards sing about. The duel in which Sevenchen would not use his feet. Shackled to the floor and facing a capable opponent in her own right, he dueled Mirintha of Tyr in a sensational mountaintop duel. Mirintha was at first baffled by how well Sevenchen could parry even without moving, but she soon saw an opportunity. Engaging his right, she swiftly somersaulted between his legs to threaten his flank. Sevenchen twisted his body to meet her with such force that both of his knees snapped right then and there.

Less a victory and more of an embarassment, Mirintha retired the blade that turned out to be Sevenchen's Folly.
Crafted to look identical to commoner's garb, the enchantments upon this suit are cleverly concealed.
Heavily improved padding makes this Assassin's Garb more resistant to crushing attacks and far more quieter to get behind one's mark.
Numerous upgrades to the toolbelt and gauntlets of this Rogue's Tunic make for far easier "delicate work."

Meticulously crafted to look similar to the armor of the Swords of the South, only someone looking closely would manage to spot the difference. Highly illegal, it's a wonder what sort of nefarious purposes someone might get up to with this.
This is obviously meant to be a replica badge of the Swords of the South.
A great start to a forgery project, the letterhead upon this document looks extremely official.

The worst thing to ruin a job is losing your cool. This pointed piece of platinum is enchanted to provide a pinprick of pain when manipulated in a pocket. Just enough to keep the user lucid and focused on the task at hand.

The burgaler's belt is really nothing more than a versatile toolbelt, with delicate lock picks and gadgets hanging from various clips around it's length.  Some open locks, some spring traps, and yet others are little manuals describing and explaining unusual devices that may be found along a thieve's.. adventures.
A belt which has many pockets, each containing some sort of chemical.

Another item made in honor of Cordor's cat population, this set of soft black leather boots give the wear the light footfalls of a cat as well as making her senses sharper. Strangely, wearing the boots for prolonged periods of time have been known to make people act extremely cat like.
A job well done is one that you're never caught doing.
This cloak is colored to help the wearer blend into their surroundings, and enchanted to make them more aware.
Cloaks are simple cloth garments used to protect the wearer from bad weather and other hazards of the open road.
This cloak conceals many pockets inside with small gadgets sewen into it, making some of the different tasks of thieves quite easier accomplished.
Cloaks are simple cloth garments used to protect the wearer from bad weather and other hazards of the open road.
This cloak was made for those who would wish to be able to alter their appearance for short periods of time.
Cloaks are simple cloth garments used to protect the wearer from bad weather and other hazards of the open road.
The Hands of Mask not only enable a great deal of nimbleness in the fingers, but they also impart the wearer with guidance on things best not stolen (at least right now).

Gloves fashioned after the martial arts of a monk named Wynter, a previous council member of Cordor who disappeared without trace and without warning. His fighting style mirrored like that of a cat; quick strikes and many. The gloves are made of a soft black cloth that are magically enhanced to quieten movements, tipped with small razors that seem to drain the life from the foe as they slice them apart.

Tormy the Blade favored anything that made him faster or more deadly...and generally when he could both. Tormy's career was cut short one night, lighting the purse of the wrong paladin in the City of Splendors.

Fabricated by the Strangest gnome of all, Kelvin, these gloves seem to take a life of their own when used to manipulate armors and weapons.  Showing an inate creativity of their own, they allow their wearer to create fantabulous new variations of gear.
These stitched leather gloves look like any average riding glove. Their true power is hidden carefully so as to not arouse suspicion that they are, in fact, deadly weapons.
Black Balls are small, enchanted balls which cause an area to become enveloped in magical darkness for a short time. Especially used by assassins for the ability to attack without being noticed.
This is a magical box of hats. Use it to choose a hat!
A small wooden box lined with red satin walls within. It holds a plethora of masks in different shapes, colors, and designs.

This bundle of magical feathers used to be a required component of casting Isaac's Greater Missile Swarm. Now well past its expiration, its power is still useful for casting a far more rudimentary version.
This rare crystal sand was a necessary component in the casting of the spell "Time Stop". Now, its magic has waned, though one may find it has some time-altering properties even still.

[[OOC: Use this item on a Hooded Cloak or Masked Cloak if you wish to destroy it.

First use will lock the target and ask if you're sure you want it destroyed. A second use will destroy the object and is not reversible.]]
A magical potion that, when drunk, will impart the same effect as a Freedom of Movement spell.
A corked bottle with a very misty liquid inside, at times not even appearing as if it's there. When drunk, the drinker develops a ghostly visage.
A bubbly, clear liquid that tastes strongly of mint. It protects the mind temporarily from any danger when drunk.
A much more potent (and expensive!) potion of Cat's Grace, lasting far longer than a regular, cheaper potion.
A liquid, dirt brown in colour, with a sour taste. When drunk, it will temporarily enhance skills that certain professions will find most useful...

A delicious, aromatic bottle of red wine.
A sour mix of questionable origin, blended with dubious fruit and a generous splash of dwarven ale. Cheap, strong, and guaranteed to get you talking (or regretting it).
Sugar-rich confections baked from batter, consuming these can give one an extra boost of energy.
These whole wheat crackers are salted and have a light buttery taste to them. Coming in small packets of 10, they're a perfect snack for people on the go.

Figs can be eaten fresh or dried, and used in jam-making. Most commercial production is in dried or otherwise processed forms, since the ripe fruit does not transport well, and once picked does not keep well.
There are many unusual items in the game. This is one of them.
Made with sheep milk, goat milk, or rothé milk, depending on what's available.
A mixture of nuts, dried fruits, and seeds. This trail mix is an adventurer's favorite treat.
There are many unusual items in the game. This is one of them.

A deep purple concoction of blackberry brandy, dark rum, and a hint of anise,
best served in a shadowed corner booth. Goes down easy, but packs a punch.
A golden-hued liqueur with a hint of citrus and honey, served in a small, ornate cup. Smooth and deceptively sweet, with a touch of luxury for the discerning thief.
A cheap, lukewarm ale with a suspicious aftertaste. Only for the truly desperate or those on a very tight budget.
A reliable, no-frills lager brewed especially for the guild. Hits the spot after a long day of "acquisitions."
A refreshing blend of herbs and spices, rumored to have calming and clarity-enhancing properties. Perfect for those who need to keep a cool head after a job.
